I can’t help but feel Vessels pain every time I listen to the songs, sometimes seeing myself when I listen. Vessel just captures the pain in a way I’ve never known.

I have so much appreciation for this band and to see the extent of Vessels hurt, to have to listen to him rip everything apart, it hits harder than expected. Each time the ending flashes from the perfect palace to the desecrated ruins, I can’t help but think it’s like a metaphor, like a glimpse from how he is on stage to how he feels inside.

Even if he never sees this, I want to say it. Thank you, Vessel, for everything you’ve done and I’m proud of you. Worship. 🖤

content:
Jesus is coming back soon! The Bible foretold all of the things that are happening in the world right now over 2,000 years ago. The world will soon fall into the 7 year tribulation, which is going to be literal hell on earth. Everything is coming together exactly like God said it would! Yes, for the world it is a hopeless situation, but the good news is that God has provided an escape through faith in Jesus Christ alone!
John 3:16: “For God so loved the world that he gave His one and only Son, that whoever believes in Him will not perish, but have everlasting life.”
We are all born sinners and doomed to spend eternity in hell. Romans 3:10 states that “There is no one righteous, not even one”.
Romans 3:23 explains: “For all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God.” We all have a sin debt that we owe God and it is so great that we can never possibly repay it. However, the good news is that Jesus paid that debt by dying and suffering the wrath of God in our place on the cross, and three days later He rose from the dead in ultimate victory over sin and death.
Romans 6:23 says: “The wages of sin is death, but the gift of God is eternal life in Christ Jesus our Lord.” God loves us more than we can even imagine and is offering every single person forgiveness and salvation, regardless of what anyone has done, if only they put their faith in Jesus Christ alone. We can never do anything to earn salvation no matter how good of a person that we think we are. Isaiah 64:6 states: “all our righteous acts are like filthy rags”. But praise God that when we accept Christ as our savior, Jesus gives us His righteousness! It’s a GIFT!
Romans 10:9-10 explains: “That if you confess with your mouth, “Jesus is Lord,” and believe in your heart that God raised him from the dead, you will be saved. For it is with your heart that you believe and are justified, and it is with your mouth that you confess and are saved.”
Romans 10:13 “Everyone who calls on the name of the Lord will be saved”.

Jesus IS Lord and the Bible says one day all will confess that and bow their knee before Him. Unfortunately, there will be many that do that right before they go into eternal torment in the lake of fire. Do it now before it is too late! Jesus is real, He is the Son of God, He gave His life for us, and three days later He rose from the dead. To this day there is an empty tomb in Jerusalem! He is coming back soon to rapture every true believer. Don’t be left behind to experience the wrath of God that’s about to fall on this world. Get saved now before it’s too late! John 14:6: (Jesus speaking) “I am the way and the truth and the life. No one comes to the Father except through me.”

Here are a couple links for further information. I am not affiliated with this website or ministry, they are simply tools that I think may help you!

content: I got really luckey in1975. I was in highschool then and working at a supermarket. I put the word out that I was looking for a 440 Challenger. After a few months a manager came up to me and said his friend had a 70 Challenger 440 for sale. That was it! It was mint with new Craigers and it was still under the 5/50 warrente! I paid his price of $1600. It was F8 green with a black int, vynal roof, race fuel cap and a great fm stereo raido. My buddy had a 68 GTX and his 440 engine came in a box with a sixpack. When he went to put the sixpack on he said he hit a hot wire and they cought fire and he didn't want them. I offered him 50 bucks fore them and the air cleaner and they were mine! I pulled the heads off for a new performance valve job and shaved the heads for higher compression. I also painted the cast intake and rebuilt the holly carbs. Got it running perfect and got the SIXPACK emblems for the hood too.

content:
I wanna know if they streamlined the attribute gains system, which would be incredibly simple for both Oblivion and Morrowind. Literally, every 2 levels into a strength skill, you get an automatic +1 to your strength. It happens behind the scenes, there's no need to plan with a pencil and paper, there's no menus you have to keep going into, etc. It would be SOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOO simple.
Also inventory management in exploration RPGs is clunky af and bogs down enjoyment. When you find an item in the wild, there should be 3 options which you can choose from: put it into your inventory, put it into your storage, or sell it immediately, with storage only being accessible in towns. Just think of all the weeks of your life you've wasted looking at menus, fast traveling back and forth between dungeons and towns, going in between different merchants, trying to remember which merchants buy what items, etc. Those are full weeks of your life you could have been playing the more enjoyable parts of those games AND a ton of other games you never got around to because of all the menu simulation shit. Think also about having to wait while your character also waits just so a shop opens up. Eliminate the day/night cycles of games and the wandering NPCs and merchants. Go back to Morrowind's merchant ethics, for Christ's sake.
These are simple, easy, quick fixes the devs could to which would cost them nothing but which would save FUCKING MILLIONS OF YEARS being wasted collectively by their customers.

content: I used to be a professional ditch-digger (read archaeologist) mainly in the South East and let me tell you that red clay of Virginia and North Carolina is a bitch to dig through!  For your next hole I recommend sharpening your shovel with a file or angle grinder to get through the roots and try doing it with flat walls on the sides (but not too deep so they don’t cave in on you).  And try doing it in levels because you start to get a feel for the contours and texture of the earth, see where one dirt changes and becomes a different kind.  We would do ours in 10cm intervals because, y’know, science.

content:
9:20 I lived in North Carolina until I was 15. I lived about 40 minutes northwest of Greensboro in the middle of the woods. My father had me and my brothers working on the land a bit—not a whole ton of work, but enough to gain an appreciation for it. Yes, the top soil can have lots of roots in the way. We need a mattock to cut through roots or bust up rocks & hard soil. Once the roots and stones are busted up, then we can more easily shovel it out.

Also, it helps to really slam a sharp shovel into those roots. It's not gentle work. We gotta really cut through those roots. Once we're at the clay, that's actually my favorite part. The clay is relatively easy and soft compared to the topsoil. 😅 It does weigh a lot. I tended to slam my shovel into the clay several times—maybe 5 or so times—to get enough ready to shovel it out.

Oh, another thing. I was over 6' by 12 years old. I was skinny (not anywhere as much muscle as I have now as an adult), but I think being taller helps with leverages on digging. I could handle the shovel like a long lever, and this helps with the forces.

Oh, and one more thing. Digging out manual labor in general can rough up the hands. We might want rougher hands on purpose, but there's a limit to how quickly our hands can adapt. If we do touch much digging over a few days, then we can really cut up the skin on our palms, and then it takes a few weeks to heal. A good way to do it is to maybe have days where we wear gloves to let the palms rest. Over time we can build very tough hands, but take it slowly so we don't end up with a mess that takes days or a few weeks to heal.

content: 7:35 😅 Yeah, the way you played AGADAH reminded me so much of Cookie Clicker or other clicking games. I'm glad you made that connection. I love clicker games. Before there was Cookie Clicker, there were other clicker games. I think maybe the first major clicker game I played was a simple flash game called "Hunter Story" that is based on the Hunter/Bowman character class from MapleStory. Hunter Story has us shooting, aiming, and eventually, just clicking the screen over and over to kill mobs. We get upgrades and skills for our bow & arrow, but the game pretty much evolves into just clicking the screen on the same spot over and over. For higher accuracy ratings per level, we had to time the clicks, but it's close to cookie clicker or universal paperclips or many other clicker games.

content:
As someone who's served in the military for awhile now, one of the most interesting and engaging parts of my entire career was digging a machine gun emplacement. Making a spot of land big enough two bodies could disappear in, covering it with brush, building and molding chairs to sit in and steps to climb out with nothing but soil. It felt good in a way I can't describe.

Despite being stationed in the middle east, traveling the world, countless hours of training, the old Vietnam tradition of digging a hole and hiding in it felt so strangely rewarding

content:
Hey Matt and whomever reads this, I just want to share an impact your channel had on someone. (Long post, no TLDR, sorry)
My dad has always been an incredibly active man; he started at age 10 working with his father doing construction during school breaks, after school, etc... His next two careers took him to airplanes and OTR. Always vehicles.
Then at age 50 he had a massive stroke. Turns out something in his blood had mutated causing it to coagulate too quickly. Before they were able to get a handle on it, he had two more strokes, three heart attacks, and countless TIA's. As you can imagine, especially for someone who has been active for their entire life, this was crushing. But he fought, and he fought hard. If you didn't know him before you'd probably not even know he'd had any issues.
Then he found out he has pancreatic cancer. This was different because there isn't really anything they can do this time. He's been told he likely wouldn't survive the surgery, that the risk/reward wasn't worth it in his case.
And this is where you come in, Matt. Dad would just sit there and stare out the window, completely disengaged with the world around him, (something very difficult to see). Then he started messing around watching YouTube, figuring out that you could watch nearly anything on there. And he found Diesel Creek. He talks so much crap to you, Matt, lol. I was watching with him one day and reminded him that you couldn't actually hear him. He turned and grinned at me, a sparkle in his eyes that hadn't been there for a loooong time. He's so engaged with your channel now. I now sit and watch with him, and he'll point out equipment his father used to have, stories about some of the things he and his brothers would try to pull to get out of work on hot summer days; even when we're out driving around he'll point to a road that he helped build, things like that.
So, in saying all of this, my main thing is to say THANK YOU. You've touched people in ways you'll never know, and likely never even imagined. But I wanted to be sure you knew about this one.

content:
Boost pressure is EXACTLY right! You have to subtract the barometric pressure (around 1bar at sea level) to the boost indicated pressure to know what your turbo is doing. If that was at 0, it means either the sensor was fault or you would be on the moon with no atmosphere.
By the way, I seriously hope you prefilled that turbo (and the oil filter) with oil before to switch that thing on... Or you're in for a bad surprise in few weeks.

author: @anthony10370

content: WRONG. when engine is not runnin barometric pressure and boost pressure should be the same because no overpressure is being produced by exhaust in the turbo. The failure state is when with the engine running there in no increase in boost pressure over barometric pressure (or there is not enough). And that not always point to the turbo, it may be a pressure leak in the conduits or the intercooler if thre is one.This usually translates into poor performance and black smoke in the eshaust, while white-blueish exhaust usualli point to a bad turbo or turbine seals (turbo needs replacing or rebuilding) if turbine does not turn freely bearing are damaged. After long sessions of hard work, let the motor run idle for a while so oil can cool the turbo, otherwise the hot turbo will burn the oil inside, crystals will form and the turbo will with time be broken again. Idle your turbo-diesels before switching them off.

content:
As a huge fan of both one and two, I can see a few things that would be great.
- I agree with others who said bigger space and bigger creatures, or ones that lurk in the dark.
- Seatruck was cute but absolutely did not compare to the cyclops. Something bigger for the final area that can hold other vehicles. Potentially, a base that can travel with you...An underwater RV in a way?

The storylines for me a big part of it, so I really liked in the first how the previous group played out and almost forced you to different locations. Please keep that. I also kinda want to know what happened to the first guy when he got back owing millions of dollars...even if its just a PDA entry.

Also personally, I really liked the story line of two so a follow up game to that would be epic, I have a few story ideas for that one...like upon arrival she is pushed/thrown into their 'alien' sea as she is seen as threat to them, and has to survive long enough to either find Alan again or a way back to the ship.

content:
BE RUTHLESS ABOUT MAIN THING from the first game: Thrill of the unknown. Keep that intact at all times. Not horror or terror. Thrill that can turn to hysteria. Make observation and exploration rewarding but keep uncertainty and danger immanent. If you deviate from that core emotional ride, it will not be Subnautica to anyone. Keep the game 'dialogue' quiet. As little dialogue as possible. only the PDA or recordings. Hearing character dialogue is like taking a TV with you camping.

Otherwise I have feature suggestions:
- make a setting where fauna can be found in biomes more or less strictly. This can add replay value once the "unknown" is impossible.
- make an in game proximity chat feature. That way people can play with friends and still feel alone when they go off by themselves. You could even have a base "whiteboard" to facilitate a restricted communication: You can talk to each other when near, or both in the same base, but if someone leaves, there can be "notes" where they took off to. Obviously discord would can break this but I would like to see this feature added so that coop doesn't completely break the tension and atmostphere.
- add base "blueprinting" so you can build a mini base fully if you have all the right resources. This is also a community feature because people can share blueprints and explore each other's bases.
- add base "moving" related to above
- Try to make ventures into leviathan and predator territories skill or strategy or preparation based. Using things like distractions increase chances through chaos, but don't let them be cheese easy. Everyone knows the invisible walls...
- Give late game unlocks for massive storage features so that "near creative mode" is the reward for building.
- DO TIMECAPSLES AGAIN.
- Allow different difficulty settings for simultaneous players. My kid and I play but I want to be on hard but he needs to be on easy or he gets overly scared.
author: @4tdaz

content:
What i'd like to see:
Bigger toolbar! of at least 7 slots. Make it a setting or simply hide empty slots once PDA is closed. Why limit it much at all? 4 slots seen here is highly concerning!
Reasonable graphics options and settings. For instance usable AA (TAA and XFAA dont count), AF, resolution scaling, frame limit and vsync Together. fsr4 and dlss4 would also be nice.
Smooth PDA interaction, as in fast open/close without control restrictions and adverse effects such as forcing view to horizon and excessively delaying camera control, with rubberbanding. This is currently extremely bad in the original game, and somewhat better(Still bad) in BZ. It was not like this originally, but got messed up with some update.
Hardcore with normal alerts like o2 etc. Those that come with the suit and PDA! Feedback to ingame happenings is important as we're not there in person to feel it. Only difference from normal survival should be 1 life.-or make it a setting.
Improved creature movement and collision. Perhaps also behavior.(hello leviathans clipping through terrain and camping shallows, gnawing at you unseen from the underground)
Scanner room hud distance indicator. Used to be a mod where icon size scaled by distance. However most good mods broke with updates.
General improvements. Going by BZ, there are issues. Lots of graphics pop-ins(max settings), even at close range. Airbubbles visible inside habitat.

content:
Couple helpful notes.
1. Attack rate and hits levels weapons not damage or difficulty. Daggers or tapping shots on bow is faster respectively.
2. Lockpicking levels based on pins set. Set 3 fail 1 to keep grinding it.
3. Basement of the Arena has free beds to use for level up without join a guild or buying a house.
4. Enemy loot layout is based on level. Your first run don’t power level or you’ll be at a massive disadvantage if you don’t know what you’re doing.
5. Mages guild dude that sells Dremora Lord dies in a quest line. This is the only place to get the spell, you cannot after he dies. Can’t remember which guy. You find him while doing the recommendations.

content:
Here is some context that people not of the culture miss:
1. Hoodoo is not a religion. It is a practice, that often in black communities is practiced in tandem with Christianity. Annie for example is never shown to practice Christianity, but she never speaks against it.
2. The choice Sammie made was not a decision of whether his father was right or wrong, but Remmick and his father used the Bible, religion, and spirituality as a means of control. Sammie made a decision out of free will, and music was the only choice that was not forced down his throat.
3. While I wouldn’t call blues a religion or equitable to it (like hoodoo, music is a practice that can work in tandem with religion), it is instead a way of life. We never see if Sammie reconciles his relationship with religion to speculate what his viewpoints on it are. Griots, like Sammie, are storytellers - that is who they are to their core and what they are put on earth to do.
4. It is not a sad ending if it was in fact Sammie’s decision to step away from religion. The Lord wants a cheerful giver, not a coerced one.
